  "title": "Introduction to EIP Sketchs",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "ad65ff3c28408ada",
      "text": "# What is this sketch?\nIt is a space for simultaneously looking at and talking about 1) the interactions of **institutions** with other institutions (of various types), 2) institutions in within the contexts of citizenship within **[[Nested Political Systems]]** communities and their institutions, and 3) institutions in the context of **place** [[Nested Ecological Systems]] (biological-geological-geographic situatedness)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4e75f51a8cf59c72",
      "text": "# What is this sketch for?\nIt provides a conceptual place and a simple way for people to have productive **conversations about ecology, politics and business** as a single dynamic system."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "70f0144b90009ccf",
      "text": "The whole point is to come to greater shared understanding (not necessarily agreement) among some particular stakeholders, and then to look for leverage points that are within their reach."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2e7da0650b962809",
      "text": "> [[Leverage points]] are available actions that have outsized effects in the desired for direction when compared to the input."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "96d2eb74cbeceaca",
      "text": "Once we think we understand enough of the dynamics, we then take actions to see if things get better or worse. Pilots are a good idea whenever possible."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "3cf7472128610bce",
      "text": "Many of our actions have unintended consequences, in particular involving the planet and future generations. Many of our actions are constrained or even opposed by the system as a whole. Therefore, it is better to understand something of leverage points and constraints before we start pushing on the levers."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b2f3799ddf33233b",
      "text": "> CAUTION: Don't sketch alone. In my experience working alone on complex social systems is a waste of time."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4077d7c5e1d9c255",
      "text": "> CAUTION: Focusing on areas where you can't get traction (cooperation or power) is a wast of time, in my experience."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1d3ce36cffb180e8",
      "text": "# How to start?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c4c37678d4b46ccc",
      "text": "> Notice that all items must be [[variables]]--changeable. The terms must invite speculation on what changes them and what else changes with they are changed. All the [[connections]] will represent [[causal relationships]], this affects that, A->B. There will be [[feedback loops]] that drive change or dampen change."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "91137f58ab0d9580",
      "text": "> The rigor of making every item a \"variable thing\" may seem weird, but it can be done and it will make the whole thing work better as you begin to have conversations. You will often create better variables as you go along."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c82982c17002d35d",
      "text": "Transcribe a \"blank\" EIP Sketch on a wall using colored sticky notes--Green for ecological recursions and Blue for political recursions. \n\nAdd a few relevant businesses or institutions using Yellow and Red (for [[publicly traded corporations]]). We will want to know where the owners live. We will want to know how decisions are made. We will want to know who the intended and actual beneficiaries are for every institution in the diagram."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "93c88271bce6bedd",
      "text": "Put yourselves into the sketch--as named individuals and relevant community groups and businesses. Provide formal names for the relevant political recursions."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "51c1701dd97f48bb",
      "text": "Name relevant ecological recursions using Green. Don't worry to much about scientific accuracy. We are trying to have conversations not debates. Find terms you can agree upon-tentatively."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b70aea0d8b96f1ec",
      "text": "# What problem(s) are you interested in talking about?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "99599ddb41efc628",
      "text": "What interests you?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "367746c5519c86f6",
      "text": "In the context of your passion and interests, which businesses, which places on earth, which political bodies (and laws/regulations) are at play?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "4158a673c9765836",
      "text": "Put them on the wall (as variables)."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "5e88f0cdec321658",
      "text": "Who are potential allies?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8cfa4c2cd00d9a1e",
      "text": "Who are potential opponents?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1267defea8a29463",
      "text": "Include their variables!"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "c0947c1f5817b73b",
      "text": "# Participation\nGet stakeholders to place their organizations as variables into the sketch and draw the causal relationships--what effects them and what do they effect. Show the directionality of each effect: changes in the same (S) or opposite (O) direction."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "fbdc137e3c7b74c5",
      "text": "Check for completeness. Are there any big relationships missing?"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "f50fcab14c77dfe6",
      "text": "Color code institutions by type: Civic Associations, Co-operatives, Private Institutions, Non-profits, Public Institutions, Publicly Traded Corporations."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7df5d6a0ce9d6be8",
      "text": "Guess at the high leverage institutions."
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "7b146a6397722517",
      "text": "# Follow on\nPut the data into a n x n matrix and have small groups code for degree of cross effect. \nFind the high leverage points.\nMake plans for a experiments in the real world."
